<biogHist>
<abstract>The Natives (Citizenship Rights) Act 1944 (023 of 1944 (8 &amp; 9 Geo. VI No. 23)) required Aboriginal people to sever all ties with their extended family and to demonstrate they had 'adopted the manner and habits of civilised life' for at least two years to gain 'full rights of citizenship'. Citizenship, once granted, could be revoked if 'civilised life' was not maintained. The Act was repealed by the Natives (Citizenship Rights) Act Repeal Act 1971.</abstract>
<p>The <span style="font-style:italic">Natives (Citizenship Rights) Act 1944</span> outlined the conditions of citizenship as the need (s.2) to 'dissolve tribal and native association' (parents, siblings and the applicant's own children excepted) and (s.5.1.a) the need for applicants to demonstrate they had 'adopted the manner and habits of civilised life' for at least two years prior to application.</p>
<p>Citizenship, once granted, could be revoked (s.7.1.a) if this manner of living was not kept up. Therefore, adults who had been removed from family groups and sent to an institution would have to choose between reuniting with their extended family and citizenship. The Act was eventually repealed by the <span style="font-style:italic">Natives (Citizenship Rights) Act Repeal Act 1971</span>.</p>

</biogHist>
</description>
